label: TurbineLoadControllerDynamics
comment: Turbine load controller function block whose behaviour is described by reference to a standard model <font color="#0f0f0f">or by definition of a user-defined model.</font>

label: TurbineLoadControllerUserDefined
comment: Turbine load controller function block whose dynamic behaviour is described by <font color="#0f0f0f">a user-defined model.</font>

label: UnderexcLim2Simplified
comment: Simplified type UEL2 underexcitation limiter. This model can be derived from UnderexcLimIEEE2. The limit characteristic (look-up table) is a single straight-line, the same as UnderexcLimIEEE2 (see Figure 10.4, IEEE 421.5-2005, Section 10.2).

label: UnderexcLimIEEE1
comment:
Type UEL1 model which has a circular limit boundary when plotted in terms of machine reactive power vs. real power output. Parameter details:
  1. Vf signal applies only if the under excitation limiter is used in combination with IEEE 421.5 models.
Reference: IEEE 421.5-2005, 10.1 and IEEE 421.5-2016, 11.2.

label: UnderexcLimIEEE2
comment:
Type UEL2 underexcitation limiter which has either a straight-line or multi-segment characteristic when plotted in terms of machine reactive power output vs. real power output. Parameter details:
  1. Vf signal applies only if the under excitation limiter is used in combination with IEEE 421.5 models.
Reference: IEEE 421.5-2005, 10.2 (limit characteristic lookup table shown in Figure 10.4). According to IEEE 421.5-2016, 11.3 the UEL2 underexcitation limiter model is being superseded by the model UEL2C (UnderexcLimIEEEUEL2C).

label: UnderexcLimIEEEUEL2C
comment:
IEEE 421.5-2016 UEL2C underexcitation limiter model. For this model, the UEL limit has either a straight-line or multisegment characteristic (piecewise linear) when plotted in terms of machine reactive power output versus real power output.

Reference: IEEE 421.5-2016, 11.4.

label: UnderexcLimX1
comment: <font color="#0f0f0f">Allis-Chalmers minimum excitation limiter.</font>

label: UnderexcLimX2
comment: <font color="#0f0f0f">Westinghouse minimum excitation limiter.</font>

label: UnderexcitationLimiterDynamics
comment: Underexcitation limiter function block whose behaviour is described by reference to a standard model <font color="#0f0f0f">or by definition of a user-defined model.</font>

label: UnderexcitationLimiterUserDefined
comment: Underexcitation limiter function block whose dynamic behaviour is described by <font color="#0f0f0f">a user-defined model.</font>

label: VAdjIEEE
comment:
IEEE voltage adjuster which is used to represent the voltage adjuster in either a power factor or VAr control system.
Reference: IEEE 421.5-2005, 11.1.

label: VAdjIEEE2
comment:
IEEE 421.5-2016 Voltage reference adjuster model. It is is used to represent the voltage adjuster in either a power factor or var control system represented by a Type 1 model.

Reference: IEEE 421.5-2016, 13.7.

label: VCompIEEEType1
comment: Terminal voltage transducer and load compensator (Type 1). This model is common to all excitation system models described in the IEEE Standard. Parameter details: - If Rc and Xc are set to zero, the load compensation is not employed and the behaviour is as a simple sensing circuit. - If all parameters (Rc, Xc and Tr) are set to zero, the standard model VCompIEEEType1 is bypassed. Reference: IEEE 421.5-2005, 4 and IEEE 421.5-2016, 5.

label: VCompIEEEType2
comment:
Terminal voltage transducer and load compensator (Type 2). This model is designed to cover the following types of compensation:
  • reactive droop;
  • transformer-drop or line-drop compensation;
  • reactive differential compensation known also as cross-current compensation.
Reference: IEEE 421.5-2005, 4 and IEEE 421.5-2016, 5.

label: VSCDynamics
comment: VSC function block whose behaviour is described by reference to a standard model <font color="#0f0f0f">or by definition of a user-defined model.</font>

label: VSCUserDefined
comment: Voltage source converter (VSC) function block whose dynamic behaviour is described by <font color="#0f0f0f">a user-defined model.</font>

label: VoltVarSettings
comment:
Volt Var Settings.

Reference: IEEE1547-2018.

label: VoltWattSettings
comment:
Volt Watt Settings.

Reference: IEEE1547-2018.

label: VoltageAdjusterDynamics
comment: Voltage adjuster function block whose behaviour is described by reference to a standard model <font color="#0f0f0f">or by definition of a user-defined model.</font>

label: VoltageAdjusterUserDefined
comment: <font color="#0f0f0f">Voltage adjuster</font> function block whose dynamic behaviour is described by <font color="#0f0f0f">a user-defined model.</font>

label: VoltageCompensatorDynamics
comment: Voltage compensator function block whose behaviour is described by reference to a standard model <font color="#0f0f0f">or by definition of a user-defined model.</font>

label: VoltageCompensatorUserDefined
comment: Voltage compensator function block whose dynamic behaviour is described by <font color="#0f0f0f">a user-defined model.</font>

label: VoltageTripSettings
comment:
Voltage Trip Settings.

Reference: IEEE1547-2018.

label: VsConverter
comment: DC side of the voltage source converter (VSC).

label: WattVarSettings
comment:
Watt Var Settings.

Reference: IEEE1547-2018.

label: WeccBESS
comment: WECC dynamics models related to battery energy storage systems (BESS).

label: WeccDERA
comment:
WECC Distributed Energy Resources Model.

Reference: The New Aggregated Distributed Energy Resources (der_a) Model for Transmission Planning Studies: 2019 Update, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2019, 3002015320.

label: WeccDERApvmod
comment: Modified WECC Distributed Energy Resources Model.

label: WeccDynamics
comment: Parent class supporting relationships to WECC standard models.

label: WeccPVD1
comment:
WECC Distributed and Small PV Plants Model. It is no longer recommended for use and WeccDERA should be used instead.
This model is included in this document for supporting existing implementations that did not migrate to WeccDERA model.

Reference:  WECC PV Power Plant Dynamic Modeling Guide 2014, 4.3.

label: WeccREEC
comment: WECC PQ Controller and Current Limit Logic.

label: WeccREECA
comment:
WECC PQ Controller and Current Limit Logic.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccREECB
comment:
WECC PQ Controller and Current Limit Logic. 
A simplified version of the electrical controls, which was previously used for PV plants but is no longer recommended. 

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccREECC
comment:
WECC PQ Controller and Current Limit Logic.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccREECD
comment:
WECC PQ Controller and Current Limit Logic (REEC_D).

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccREGCA
comment:
WECC Generator-Converter Model.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccREGCB
comment:
WECC Generator/Converter model (REGC_B) which is an extension of the REGC_A model by changing the network interface between the generator/converter model from a current-source to a voltage-source.

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccREGCC
comment:
WECC Generator/Converter model (REGC_C) which is an alternative of the REGC_B model. This model is an advanced draft which is expected to be finalised by WECC.

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccREPCA
comment:
WECC Plant Controller.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccREPCC
comment:
WECC Plant controller model (REPC_C).

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccTIOCRS
comment: Time Inverse Overcurrent Relay Standard (TIOCRS) model by WECC. The details on this relay are described in WECC Generic Overcurrent Relay Model, 2013.

label: WeccWT12T
comment:
WECC Two-mass Drive Train Model.

Reference: [1] Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.
[2] https://www.esig.energy/wiki-main-page/wt1-generic-wind-model/.

label: WeccWT1PB
comment:
WECC Pitch Controller (Type 1).

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccWT2E
comment:
WECC External Resistance Controller.

Reference: https://www.esig.energy/wiki-main-page/wt2-generic-wind-model/#Rotor_Resistance_Control_Model_.28WT2E.29.

label: WeccWTGARA
comment:
WECC Aero-Dynamic Model.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccWTGIBFFRA
comment:
WECC WTGIBFFR_A model. Auxiliary control model representing the so-called inertial-based fast-frequency response (IBFFR) controls.

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccWTGPB
comment:
WECC Mechanical side model (WTGP_B).

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccWTGPTA
comment:
WECC Pitch Controller (Type 3).

References: 
- Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.
- https://www.nerc.com/comm/PC/NERCModelingNotifications/Modeling_Notification_-_PitchControls.pdf.

label: WeccWTGTA
comment:
WECC Drive-Train Model.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccWTGTB
comment:
WECC WTGT_B model. A drive-train “emulation” model where the only input is the electrical power (Pe) of the generator and mechanical power (Pm) is simply taken to be a filtered value of Pe.

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WeccWTGTRQA
comment:
WECC Torque Controller.

Reference: Model User Guide for Generic Renewable Energy System Models, EPRI, Palo Alto, CA: 2018, 3002014083.

label: WeccWTGWGOA
comment:
WECC WTGWGO_A model. A simple generic model, as an auxiliary control which can be used to “emulate” this supplemental control.

Reference: WECC REMWG, Proposal for new features for the renewable energy system generic models, 2021.

label: WindAeroConstIEC
comment:
Constant aerodynamic torque model which assumes that the aerodynamic torque is constant.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.1.1.

label: WindAeroConstIEC2
comment:
Constant aerodynamic torque module which assumes that the aerodynamic torque is constant.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2020, 7.2.1.

label: WindAeroOneDimIEC
comment:
One-dimensional aerodynamic model.  
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.1.2.

label: WindAeroOneDimIEC2
comment:
One-dimensional aerodynamic module.  
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2020, 7.2.2.

label: WindAeroTwoDimIEC
comment:
Two-dimensional aerodynamic model.  
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.1.3.

label: WindAeroTwoDimIEC2
comment:
Two-dimensional aerodynamic module.  
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2020, 7.2.3.

label: WindContCurrLimIEC
comment:
Current limitation model.  The current limitation model combines the physical limits and the control limits.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.5.8.

label: WindContCurrLimIEC2
comment:
Current limitation module.  The current limitation module combines the physical limits and the control limits.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2020, 7.7.6.

label: WindContPType3IEC
comment:
P control model type 3.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.5.4.

label: WindContPType3IEC2
comment:
P control module type 3.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2020, 7.7.2.

label: WindContPType4aIEC
comment:
P control model type 4A.
Reference: IEC 61400-27-1:2015, 5.6.5.5.

label: WindContPType4aIEC2
